ğŸ”§ Challenges & Debugging (GitHub â†” AWS)

During this project, I encountered multiple issues while integrating GitHub Actions with Amazon S3 for automated deployment. 
Below are the key problems and how they were resolved.

1ï¸âƒ£ GitHub Actions â€“ AWS Credentials Not Loading

Error:

Credentials could not be loaded from any providers


Cause:

AWS credentials were:

Misformatted in GitHub Secrets, or

Previously exposed and automatically quarantined by AWS

Resolution:

Created a new IAM access key

Stored credentials correctly in GitHub Repository Secrets:

AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID

AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY

Removed the compromised key

2ï¸âƒ£ S3 AccessDenied (ListObjectsV2)

Error:

AccessDenied: not authorized to perform s3:ListBucket


Cause:

IAM user lacked proper S3 permissions

Bucket name in the IAM policy did not match the actual S3 bucket

Resolution:

Attached a least-privilege IAM policy allowing:

s3:ListBucket

s3:GetObject

s3:PutObject

s3:DeleteObject

Ensured the policy referenced the exact bucket name

ğŸ“˜ Key Lessons Learned

IAM explicit deny overrides allow

GitHub Secrets must use the NAME = VALUE format

Least-privilege IAM policies are critical for secure deployments

Small misconfigurations can break CI/CD pipelines
